`ctx-scan`'s binary entry point — parses argv, picks a mode, and streams human-readable output to stdout; all actual logic lives in the `ctx_scan` lib crate (`cli` module) and `ctx_summarize::agent::SubprocessAgent`.

Mode dispatch order matters and is fail-fast on the cheapest checks first: `--contract` (checked via raw `std::env::args()` before `clap::Parser::parse()` runs, so it wins over the required `<dir>` positional) → `dry_run` → `check` → `prune` → `stop_hook` → default scan/update. Only the last path constructs a `SubprocessAgent`, so the first five modes never need `CTX_AGENT_CMD` or an API key.

`run_stop_hook` is fail-open by design: it swallows every error from `stop_hook(...)` and always returns `ExitCode::SUCCESS`, because this path runs on an agent's session-stop hook and must never break or bill the session — regeneration is expected to happen post-session instead.

`exit_of(result: Result<(), ctx_scan::error::ScanError>) -> ExitCode` is the shared mapper for the four agent-free modes (dry-run/check/prune scan-update), converting `Err` to exit code 1 with a `ctx-scan: {e}` message on stderr. `SubprocessAgent::from_env_or_dotenv` failure exits with code 2 instead, distinguishing agent-construction failures from scan-logic failures.

`emit` deliberately ignores broken-pipe/write errors (e.g. `| head` truncating output) rather than panicking.